An ECDE centre has adopted the 21st century learning model to support learning in line with changing, global trends.Oshwal Academy, Nairobi, has employed activity-based learning and use of devices such as iPads, smart phones, laptops and Apple television in their learning programmes.The project will enable children to transition from old-learning methods to practical approaches, hence, having a better learning experience.&ldquo;The new classroom anchored in technology seeks to enhance creativity, innovation, collaboration and other social skills among children following the rapidly changing demands of the 21st century,&rdquo; head of nursery Munira Adamjee said.She said children will flourish by taking their own, but guided direction in learning.The classrooms have features, which are designed to improve learning. They are zoned to support personalised learning, collaboration, research and quiet study.